text: S‑Bridged Thioether and Structure-Diversiﬁed Angucyclinone Derivatives from the South China Sea-Derived Micromonospora echinospora SCSIO 04089 Zhuangjie Fang, Xiaodong Jiang, Qingbo Zhang,* Liping Zhang, Wenjun Zhang, Chunfang Yang, Haibo Zhang, Yiguang Zhu, and Changsheng Zhang* ABSTRACT: Angucyclinces belong to the class of aromatic polyketides and display a wide variety of structure diversity and pharmaceutical signiﬁcance. Herein we report the isolation, structure elucidation, and bioactivity evaluation of structure- diversiﬁed angucyclinone derivatives and anthracene from the South China Sea-derived Micromonospora echinospora SCSIO including a thioether, gephysulfuromycin (1), two new 04089, benzo[b]phenanthridines, homophenanthroviridone (2) and ho- mophenanthridonamide (3), a new benzo[b]ﬂuorene, homo- stealthin D (4), a new naphtho[2,3-b]benzofuran, nenesfuran (5), a new naphthoquinone, WS-5995 D (6) and a new anthracene, nenesophanol (7), together with three known compounds (8−10). Their structures were elucidated by extensive spectroscopic analyses. The structures of 1−3 and 5−8 were conﬁrmed by X-ray crystallographic analyses. Gephysulfuromycin (1) featured a rare single S-bridged 3,12a-epithiotetraphene skeleton. Homophenanthroviridone (2) was found to be cytotoxic to SF-268, MCF-7, and HepG2 cell lines with IC50 values of 5.4 ± 0.4, 6.8 ± 0.3, and 1.4 ± 0.1 μM, respectively. Compound 2 was also active against Gram- positive bacteria with MIC (minimal inhibition concentration) values ranging 2−4 μg mL−1. A ngucyclines are an important

family of aromatic polyketides with structural diversity and various bio- activities.1 Generally, angucyclines are derived from type II polyketide synthases (PKSs) and undergo unusual structure rearrangements with further decoration by post-PKS tailoring modiﬁcations such as oxidations and glycosylations.1,2 Typical angucyclines are characterized by angular tetracyclic benz[a]- anthracene structural skeletons.3 In contrast, atypical angucy- clines are deﬁned as aromatic polyketides that are biosynthe- sized via oxidative ring opening and rearrangement of intermediates with typical benz[a]anthracene skeletons.4 Lomaiviticins,5 kinamycins,6 nenestatins,7 and ﬂuostatins8 are benzoﬂuorene-containing atypical angucyclines with a broad spectrum of antibacterial activities and potent cytotoxic- ities.4−6,9 Especially, lomaiviticin A shows cytotoxicity at nanomolar to picomolar concentrations by causing DNA damage through a radical-based mechanism and is under preclinical studies as an anticancer agent.10 Recent studies have identiﬁed the biosynthesis gene clusters for these atypical angucyclines7,8e,11 and provided a basis to elucidate key enzymes involved in their pathways and generate structural variants.8h,11d,12 We have previously reported the isolation of nenestatin A and the identiﬁcation of the nes biosynthetic gene cluster from Micromonospora echinospora SCSIO 04089, an isolate from a sediment sample at the depth of 3025 m from the northern Cite This: https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.jnatprod.0c00719 © XXXX American Chemical Society and American Society of Pharmacognosy

South China Sea.7 In this study, we reported the isolation, structure elucidation, and bioactivity evaluation of six angucyclinone-derived new products and a new anthracene from M. echinospora SCSIO 04089 by adding macroporous resin HP20 to the fermentation medium, including a thioether, gephysulfuromycin (1), two new benzo[b]phenanthridines, homophenanthroviridone (2) and homophenanthridonamide (3), a new benzo[b]ﬂuorene, homostealthin D (4), a new naphtho[2,3-b]benzofuran, nenesfuran (5), a new naphtho- quinone, WS-5995 D (6), and a new anthracene, nenesophanol (7), together with three known compounds, homodehydror- abelomycin E (8),7,13 homorabelomycin (9),13 and (−)-ho- moseongomycin (10).14 The structures of the six new compounds (1−3 and 5−7) were unequivocally established by X-ray crystallographic analyses, especially for the sulfur- bridged thioether gephysulfuromycin (1). Homophenanthroviridone (2) was isolated as red needle crystals. The molecular formula of 2 was established to be C19H13NO4 by HRESIMS. Careful comparison of the NMR data demonstrated that the structures of 2 and phenanthroviri- done8d,17 were highly similar. The only diﬀerence was that the methyl (δ H 21.4/2.56, CH3-13) in phenanthroviridone was replaced with an ethyl group (δ H 28.6/2.87, CH2-13; 14.4/ 1.37, CH3-14) in 2. This assignment was conﬁrmed by the HMBC correlations from H2-13/H3-14 to C-3 and from H-2/ H-4 to C-13 (Table 1, Figure 1) and a single-crystal X-ray diﬀraction analysis (Figure 1, Table S1). Homophenanthridonamide (3) was isolated as red needle crystals. The molecular formula of 3 was determined as C19H13NO5 by HRESIMS. A detailed comparison of the NMR data of 3 and 2 indicated that they were structurally highly similar and only diﬀered from each other at C-5. The H-5 signal (δ H 9.51) in 2 was absent in 3. Meanwhile, the sp2 hybrid methine at C-5 (δ H 160.4/9.51) in 2 was not found in 3, either. Instead, a ketone carbonyl carbon (δ C 160.2) was observed in 3, which was conﬁrmed by the HMBC correlation from H-4 to C-5 (Table 1, Figure 1). Finally, the structure of 3 was established by a single-crystal X-ray diﬀraction analysis (Figure 1, Table S1).

Thioether compounds have been reported from plants,25 animals,26 and microorganisms,27 with a variety of frameworks and diverse bioactivities.28 The formation of a thioether bond in natural products has been studied in diverse biosynthetic pathways.29 In most cases, cysteine was the sulfur donor for thioether-containing natural products that are originated from NRPSs (nonribosomal peptide synthetases) pathways or RiPPs (ribosomally synthesized and post-translationally modiﬁed peptides).29 For example, a C−S bond was usually formed in lantibiotics through an intramolecular Michael-type addition of the cysteine thiol to dehydroalanine or dehydrobutyrine.30 A P450 monooxygenase, SgvP, was reported to catalyze the cysteine thiol-based C−S bond formation in griseoviridin.31 The radical SAM (S-adenosylmethionine) enzyme AlbA was proposed to mediate a radical C−S coupling in subtilosin A biosynthesis.32 Interestingly, a pyridoxal phosphate-dependent domain within the leinamycin polyketide synthase was identiﬁed to catalyze a C−S cleavage to support cysteine as the sulfur source in leinamycins.24 Non-cysteine-mediated sulfur incorporation has rarely been reported in natural product biosynthesis. For example, sulfur-carrier proteins from primary metabolic pathways were demonstrated for 2- thiosugar biosynthesis,33 and mycothiol was shown to be the sulfur donor in the biosynthesis of lincomycin.34 In this study, gephysulfuromycin (1) was characterized to contain a rare S- bridged thioether moiety. Plausible Biosynthetic Pathway of 1, 8, and 9

In this study, the addition of HP20 resin into fermentation cultures of the deep-sea-derived M. echinospora SCSIO 04089 led to the isolation of six new angucyclinone derivatives, including a thioether, gephysulfuromycin (1), two new benzo[b]phenanthridines, homophenanthroviridone (2) and homophenanthridonamide (3), a new benzo[b]ﬂuorene, homostealthin D (4), a new naphtho[2,3-b]benzofuran, nenesfuran (5), a new naphthoquinone, WS-5995-D (6), and a new anthracene, nenesophanol (7), together with three known compounds (8−10). Gephysulfuromycin (1) features a single S-bridged thioether bond, which is rarely found in natural products. The plausible biosynthetic pathways of 1, 8, and 9 were proposed; especially, the incorporation of the sulfur in 1 was hypothesized. Homophenanthroviridone (2) was found to show cytotoxicity and antibacterial activity. These ﬁndings add a new example of resin-based discovery of novel natural products from marine-derived microorganisms and outline a future direction to delineate the mechanism and enzymes for sulfur incorporation in microbial secondary metabolites.

General Experimental Procedures. Melting points were recorded on an SGWX-5 micromelting point meter (Shanghai). UV spectra were recorded on a UV-2600 spectrophotometer (Shimadzu). IR spectra were measured on an IR Aﬃnity-1 FT-IR spectrometer (Shimadzu). Optical rotations were measured with an MCP 500 polarimeter (Anton Paar). 1H, 13C, and 2D NMR spectra were recorded on a Bruker AV-500 MHz NMR spectrometer (Bruker Biospin GmbH) or Bruker AVANCE III HD 700 MHz NMR spectrometer (Bruker Biospin GmbH), with TMS as an internal standard. HRESIMS data were measured using a MaXis 4G UHR- TOFMS spectrometer (Bruker Daltonics Inc.). Materials for column chromatography (CC) were silica gel (100−200 mesh; 300−400 mesh; Jiangyou Silica Gel Development, Inc.), Sephadex LH-20 (40− 70 μm; Amersham Pharmacia Biotech AB), and YMC*GEL ODS-A (12 nm S-50 μm; YMC Company Ltd.). Thin-layer chromatography (TLC, 0.1−0.2 or 0.3−0.4 mm) was conducted with precoated glass plates (silica gel GF254, 10−40 nm, Jiangyou Silica Gel Development, Inc.), Medium-pressure liquid chromatography (MPLC) was performed with automatic ﬂash chromatography (Cheetahtmmp 200, Bonna-Agela Technologies Co., Ltd.) with a monitoring wavelength of 220 nm and a collecting wavelength of 254 nm. Semipreparative HPLC was performed on a Hitachi HPLC station (Hitachi-L2130) with a diode array detector (Hitachi L-2455) using a Phenomenex ODS column (250 mm × 10.0 mm, 5 μm; Phenomenex, USA).

Fermentation, Extraction, and Isolation. The strain M. echinospora SCSIO 040897 was resurrected on an ATCC172 (soluble starch 20.0 g L−1, glucose 10.0 g L−1 yeast extract 5.0 g L−1, Aobox casein 5.0 g L−1, CaCO3 19.0 g L−1, artiﬁcial sea salt 10.0 g L−1, pH 7.0) agar plate for 7 days at 28 °C and then was transferred to a 250 mL Erlenmeyer ﬂask containing 50 mL of A1 medium (soluble starch 10.0 g L−1, yeast extract 4.0 g L−1, bacterial peptone 2.0 g L−1, artiﬁcial sea salt 10.0 g L−1, pH 7.0) for incubation at 28 °C, 200 rpm for 3 days. The seed cultures were then transferred to a 1000 mL Erlenmeyer ﬂask containing 200 mL of the N4 medium (soluble starch 15.0 g L−1, ﬁsh peptone 8.0 g L−1, bacterial peptone 5.0 g L−1, glycerol 7.5 g L−1, CaCO3 2.0 g L−1, KBr 0.2 g L−1, artiﬁcial sea salt 30.0 g L−1, prewashed HP20 resin 5%, v/v, pH 7.0). A total of 30 L of cultures was prepared and incubated at 28 °C, 200 rpm for 7 days. The secondary metabolites were absorbed by HP20 resin, and the color of the resin changed from white to pink. The pink-colored HP20 resin was collected by ﬁltration. The resin was then washed with 10 L of acetone several times to aﬀord 15 g of an organic extract after drying under vacuum. X-ray Crystallographic Analysis. Single crystals of 1−3 and 5−8 were obtained in CH3OH. The suitable crystals were selected, and the crystal data were recorded on an XtaLAB AFC12 (RINC): Kappa single diﬀractometer, with Cu Kα radiation (λ = 1.54184 Å). A single crystal was kept at 100.01(10) K during the data collection. Using Olex2,35 the crystal structures were solved by the ShelXT36 structure solution program with Intrinsic Phasing and reﬁned with the ShelXL37 reﬁnement package using Least Squares minimization. The Olex2 Solvent Mask has been applied in the reﬁnement of compound 8.

Cytotoxic Activity Assay. Compounds 1−10 were evaluated for their cytotoxic activities against SF-268, MCF-7, and HepG2 cell lines with the SRB method.20 Cells (180 μL) with a density of 3 × 104 cells mL−1 of media were seeded onto 96-well plates and incubated for 24 h at 37 °C, 5% CO2. Compounds 1−10 were dissolved in DMSO to appropriate concentrations, respectively, and then, 20 μL of various concentrations (ﬁnal concentrations were at 16, 8, 4, 2, 1, and 0.5 μM) of compounds were added to the plate wells, which were further incubated for 72 h at 37 °C. After incubation, cell monolayers were ﬁxed with 50% (wt/v) trichloroacetic acid (50 μL) and stained for 30 min with 0.4% (wt/v) SRB dissolved in 1% acetic acid. Unbound dye was removed by washing repeatedly with 1% acetic acid. The protein- bound dye was dissolved in 10 mM Tris-base solution (200 μL) for the determination of OD (optical density) at 570 nm using a microplate reader. The cytotoxic compound cisplatin was used as a positive control. DMSO was used as a negative control. All data were obtained in triplicate and presented as means ± SD. IC50 values were calculated with the SigmaPlot 10.0 software using a nonlinear curve- ﬁtting method.

Antibacterial Assays. Antimicrobial activities of compounds 1− 10 were measured against ﬁve indicator strains, Staphylococcus aureus ATCC 29213, Bacillus thuringensis SCSIO BT01, Bacillus subtilis 1064, Micrococcus luteus SCSIO ML01, and methicillin-resistant Staph- ylococcus aureus (MRSA) shhs-A1, by the broth micro dilution method.38 The indicator strains were grown for 12 h on a rotary shaker at 37 °C. Cultures were diluted with sterilized medium to achieve an optical absorbance of 0.04−0.06 at 600 nm, then diluted 1000-fold before being added into 96-well micro titer plates. Three replicates of each compound were tested in dilution series ranging from 64 to 0.25 μg mL−1.
